{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2024-01-03","name":"Cynan ap Maredudd, of Caron","nameForms":[{"lang":"und-Latn","fullText":"Cynan ap Maredudd, of Caron","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"Cynan"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"ap Maredudd,"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Suffix","value":"of Caron"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"gender":"Male","lifespan":"1240–1295","fullLifespan":"1240–1295","portrait":{"url":"https://tree-portraits-pgp.familysearchcdn.org/uenkm/thumb200s.jpg","@type":"ImageObject"},"birthDate":"+1240","birthPlace":{"address":"Cardiganshire, Wales","geo":{"latitude":52.08417,"longitude":-4.65792,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"deathDate":"+1295","deathPlace":{"address":"Hereford, Herefordshire, England","geo":{"latitude":52.0558,"longitude":-2.7172,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"userCertifiedLifeSummary":"Cynan ap Maredudd († 1297) was a Welsh lord of Deheubarth.\n\nOrigin \nCynan ap Maredudd was of the Dinefwr dynasty. He was a son of Maredudd ap Owain, whose dominions covered central Ceredigion south of the Ystwyth. After his father's death in 1265, he shared the dominion with his brothers Owain and Gruffydd, with Trefilan Castle presumably remaining the common seat of the three dominions. As \"miserable chiefs\" they ruled in Ceredigion.\n\nRole during Edward I's first campaign in Wales \nLike his father, Cynan was a vassal of Llywelyn ap Gruffydd, Prince of Wales. However, during the first campaign of the English King Edward I. he submitted like his brother Gruffydd in May 1277 to the English general Payn de Chaworth. Chaworth sent him to Worcester, where he, along with Gruffydd and the Welsh lords Rhys Wyndod and Rhys Fychan, were to pay homage to the king on 1 July. He then had to take part in further fighting in West Wales on the side of the English conquerors.\n\nLoss of his dominion during the conquest of Wales \nHowever, like his brother Gruffydd, Cynan did not accept his new role as vassal to the English king after the Treaty of Aberconwy, leading to conflicts with Robert de Tibetot, the royal justiciar of South Wales. Tibetot tried to centralize administration and did not accept the old Welsh law. Already on May 18, 1278, Cynan, together with his brother Gruffydd and Rhys Wyndod, had visited the defeated Llywelyn ap Gruffydd in his residence at Dolwyddelan Castle. However, Cynan also attempted to acquire the lands of Rhys Fychan ingenau'r Glyn by suing him in court, accusing him of illegitimate birth (with the result that he was not entitled to an inheritance). In March 1282, Cynan supported the attack on Aberystwyth Castle by Gruffydd and Rhys Fychan. He then fought against the advancing English armies. Finally, in September, an English army, supported by Rhys ap Maredudd of Dryslwyn Castle, took Trefilan Castle. Cynan narrowly escaped and took refuge in the Highlands of Gwynedd . There he surrendered to English troops in January 1283. He was now supposed to secure North Ceredigion against the fugitive Dafydd ap Gruffydd on behalf of the English, but he now joined Dafydd until he too had to surrender in August 1283. However, he was not convicted as a traitor, only imprisoned for a time at Bridgnorth Castle in Shropshire.\n\nLater life \nAfter his release, Cynan was able to return to West Wales. He may have been one of the leaders of the Welsh Rebellion in West Wales in 1294 alongside Maelgwn ap Rhys, leading raids as far as Pembrokeshire, although this is not certain. After the collapse of the uprising, he fled and was eventually recognized and arrested in 1295, despite his disguise, as a leper near Brecon. Again he was not condemned as a traitor but, like his brother, fought as a mercenary in the English army in Flanders during the Franco-English War in 1297, where he is believed to have died.\n\nfamily \nCynan's daughter Gwenllian married the Welsh nobleman Gruffydd Llwyd.\nhttps://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cynan_ap_Maredudd\n\nCynan ap Maredudd (died 1295) was a Welsh nobleman who assumed leadership of the Welsh revolt of Madog ap Llywelyn in the mid-Wales area in 1294 and 1295.\n\nHe is recorded in the Welsh chronicle Brut y Tywysogyon as having jointly led the revolt in Deheubarth with Maelgwn ap Rhys (died 1295), but this seems unlikely given his known activities were confined to territories well to the north of those of Maelgwn. He is known to have besieged Builth Castle, and also attacked the castle at Cefnllys. After the collapse of the revolt in the summer of 1295, he was captured, apparently at Hereford, and executed.\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cynan_ap_Maredudd","sourceList":[{"title":"English Wikipedia: Cynan ap Maredudd","sourceType":"DEFAULT","sourceLink":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cynan_ap_Maredudd","sourceUri":"QCJ1-Q4Z"},{"title":"German Wikipedia: Cynan ap Maredudd","sourceType":"DEFAULT","sourceLink":"https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cynan_ap_Maredudd","sourceUri":"QCJB-32N"}],"events":[{"name":"Birth","sources":"0","year":"1240","date":"1240","place":"Cardiganshire, Wales"},{"name":"Death of Parent","sources":"0","year":"1265","date":"Apr 1265","place":"Cardigan Uch Ayron, Cardiganshire, Wales","age":"25","id":"GSVP-HPF"},{"name":"Death","sources":"1","year":"1295","date":"1295","place":"Hereford, Herefordshire, England","age":"55"}],"parent":[{"name":"Maredudd ab Owain Lord of Ceridigion","gender":"Male","lifespan":"1215–1265","birthDate":"+1215","deathDate":"+1265-04","age":50,"portrait":{"url":"https://tree-portraits-pgp.familysearchcdn.org/2knkm/thumb64.jpg","@type":"ImageObject"},"@type":"Person","identifier":"GSVP-HPF","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/GSVP-HPF/maredudd-ab-owain-lord-of-ceridigion-1215-1265","published":true},{"name":"Eleanor ferch Maelgwn Fychan","gender":"Female","lifespan":"1225–Female","birthDate":"A+1225","@type":"Person","identifier":"G6HM-D2N","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/G6HM-D2N/eleanor-ferch-maelgwn-fychan-1225","published":true}],"sibling":[{"name":"Owain ap Maredudd","gender":"Male","lifespan":"1240–1275","birthDate":"+1240","deathDate":"+1275","age":35,"portrait":{"url":"https://tree-portraits-pgp.familysearchcdn.org/zenkm/thumb64.jpg","@type":"ImageObject"},"@type":"Person","identifier":"GXKT-JGH","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/GXKT-JGH/owain-ap-maredudd-1240-1275","published":true},{"name":"Cynan ap Maredudd, of Caron","gender":"Male","lifespan":"1240–1295","birthDate":"+1240","deathDate":"+1295","age":55,"portrait":{"url":"https://tree-portraits-pgp.familysearchcdn.org/uenkm/thumb200s.jpg","@type":"ImageObject"},"@type":"Person","identifier":"LVSR-2M7","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/LVSR-2M7/cynan-ap-maredudd-1240-1295","published":true},{"name":"Gwenllian Ferch Maredudd de Deuheubarth","gender":"Female","lifespan":"1242–Female","birthDate":"A+1242","@type":"Person","identifier":"GGH5-KPT","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/GGH5-KPT/gwenllian-ferch-maredudd-de-deuheubarth-1242","published":false},{"name":"Gruffydd ap Maredudd","gender":"Male","lifespan":"–1319","deathDate":"A+1319","@type":"Person","identifier":"G2M5-PPP","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/G2M5-PPP/gruffydd-ap-maredudd-1319","published":true}],"spouse":[{"name":"Mrs. Cynan ap Maredudd","gender":"Female","lifespan":"1235–Female","birthDate":"A+1235","@type":"Person","identifier":"G624-B61","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/G624-B61/mrs.-cynan-ap-maredudd-1235","published":true}],"children":[{"name":"Gwenllian Verch Conan","gender":"Female","lifespan":"–Female","otherParentId":"G624-B61","@type":"Person","identifier":"GXTS-X31","url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/GXTS-X31/gwenllian-verch-conan-","published":true}],"ageAtDeath":55,"@type":"Person","@context":"http://schema.org","identifier":"LVSR-2M7","memories":0,"photos":1,"stories":0,"sources":2,"nameSources":2,"genderSources":2,"url":"https://ancestors.familysearch.org/en/LVSR-2M7/cynan